The 6-bit Rule: While a byte is 8 bits, Base64 looks at data in 6-bit chunks. This is why every 3 bytes of data (24 bits) results in exactly 4 Base64 characters ($6 \times 4 = 24$).
Efficiency: Because it uses a larger alphabet than Hex, Base64 is roughly 33% more space-efficient for representing binary data as text.Padding: You may sometimes see = 
characters at the end of Base64 strings; these are padding characters used to ensure the binary data fits the 6-bit alignment perfectly if the input isn't a multiple of 3 bytes.
